       "type": "compose",
       "q": "Exercise 1 (after Section 17). In the following selection from Thoreau, notice how each sentence begins; then compare it with one of your own themes and report what you find. 'I was witness to events of a less peaceful character. One day when I went out to my woodpile, or rather my pile of stumps, I observed two large ants, the one red, and the other much larger, nearly half an inch long, and black, fiercely contending with each other. Having once got hold, they never let go, but struggled and wrestled and rolled on the chips incessantly. Looking farther, I was surprised to find that the chips were covered with such combatants.'",
       "model": "In Thoreau's selection the sentences begin in many different ways. One opens with the subject ('I was witness'), the next with a time phrase ('One day when I went out'), the next with a participle ('Having once got hold'), and another again with a participle ('Looking farther'). Hardly any two begin alike, and not one begins with 'and.' When I compare this with my own theme, I find that I have begun several sentences in a row with 'I' and joined others with 'and,' so that my writing sounds far more monotonous than his. To improve the euphony I would change some of those beginnings, opening with a phrase or a participle as Thoreau does.",
