     "id": "comp-10-2",
     "title": "Stating the Proposition Clearly",
     "concept": "framing a precise, debatable claim before you argue",
     "summary": "Before you can prove anything, you must state exactly what you are claiming, in a clear and definite proposition.",
     "explanation": "An argument is only as clear as the proposition behind it. Before you try to convince anyone else, you must know **exactly** what *you* believe. Writing your belief out as a single sentence forces your own thinking to become sharp and definite. A proposition can take three forms: a **declarative sentence** (\"Athletics should be limited\"), a **resolution** (\"Resolved, that athletics should be limited\"), or a **question** (\"Should athletics be limited?\"). The form does not matter much, and the proposition need not be the very first sentence you write, but it must be perfectly clear in your mind before you begin. Many weak arguments fail because the claim is **too vague**. Take \"Athletics should be abolished\": all athletics? school teams only? for every age? A good proposition is narrow enough that everyone knows precisely what is being claimed, so the debate cannot dissolve into quibbling over what the words mean. Propositions come in two kinds. A **proposition of fact** claims that something actually is or happened (\"The new law reduced accidents\"). A **proposition of theory** (or policy) claims what *should* be done or believed (\"The town should pass the new law\"). Knowing which kind you have tells you what sort of proof you will need.",
     "lead": "These are the complete Sections 171 and 172, beginning with the headings \"Proposition of Fact and Proposition of Theory\" and \"Statement of the Proposition.\" They separate propositions of fact from propositions of theory, list the three forms a proposition can take, and insist you fix your own belief before you argue. The factual examples (Nero, Joan of Arc, Barbara Frietchie, Sheridan, Homer) are simply illustrations.",
     "original": "171. Proposition of Fact and Proposition of Theory.\n\nSome propositions state facts and some propositions state theories. Every argument therefore aims either to prove the occurrence of a fact or the truth of a theory. The first would attempt to show the actual or probable truth of a specific proposition ; for example :\n\nNero was guilty of burning Rome. Joan of Arc was burned at the stake. Barbara Frietchie actually existed. Sheridan never made the ride from Winchester. Homer was born at Chios.\n\nThe second would try to establish the probable truth of a general theory ; for example :\n\nA college education is a profitable investment. Light is caused by a wave motion of ether.\n\n172. Statement of the Proposition.\n\nThe subject about which we argue may be stated in any one of the three forms discussed in Section 74 ; that is, as a declarative sentence, a resolution, or a question. The statement does not necessarily appear first in the argument, but it must be clearly formulated in the mind of the writer before he attempts to argue. Before trying to convince others he must know exactly what he himself believes, and the attempt to state his belief in the form of a proposition will assist in making his own thought clear and definite.\n\nIf we are going to argue concerning elective studies, we should first of all be sure that we understand the meaning of the term ourselves. Then we must consider carefully what we believe about it, and state our proposition so that it shall express exactly this belief. On first thought we may believe the proposition that pupils should be allowed to choose their own studies. But is this true of all pupils in the grades as well as in the high schools ? Or is it true only of the upper classes in the high school or only for college students ? Can you state this proposition so that it will express your own belief on the subject ?",
     "keyTerms": [
      {
       "term": "Proposition of fact",
       "def": "a claim that something is, was, or will be the case (true or false in reality)"
      },
      {
       "term": "Proposition of theory",
       "def": "a claim about what should be done or believed (also called a proposition of policy)"
      },
      {
       "term": "Resolution",
       "def": "a proposition stated in formal 'Resolved, that ...' form, common in debate"
      },
      {
       "term": "Vague claim",
       "def": "a proposition so broad or unclear that people argue about its meaning instead of its truth"
      }
     ],
