     "title": "Metaphor and Personification",
     "concept": "the implied comparison, and the metaphor that gives life to lifeless things",
     "summary": "A metaphor is the same comparison as a simile, but implied rather than expressed: it says one object IS another. Personification is a special metaphor that attributes life, or the traits of persons, to lifeless things, animals, or even abstract ideas.",
     "explanation": "A **metaphor** makes exactly the same comparison a simile does, but it leaves out the open words of comparison. Where a simile says one object is *like* another, a metaphor says one object **is** another. Brooks notes that the two figures are essentially the same in their comparison, and that you can usually turn one into the other with ease: \"the phalanx stood like a wall\" (simile) becomes \"the phalanx, a living wall\" (metaphor). **Personification** is a special kind of metaphor. In it we attribute **life** to something lifeless, or we give the **characteristics of persons** to objects, to animals, or even to abstract ideas. When Longfellow writes that the stooping sun *upgathers his spent shafts*, the sun is treated as a living archer; when an abstract idea like Time is called a *cunning workman*, an idea is given the traits of a person. Personification is one of the most natural figures, and it gives writing both vividness and warmth.",
     "lead": "These two readings define the metaphor as an implied comparison and personification as a special metaphor that breathes life into lifeless things. Note the older rule that a simile says one object is LIKE another while a metaphor says one object IS another.",
     "original": "89. Metaphor. - A metaphor differs from a simile in that the comparison is implied rather than expressed. They are essentially the same as far as the comparison is concerned, and usually the one kind may be easily changed to the other. In a simile we say that one object is like another, in a metaphor we say that one object is another.\n\n90. Personification. - Personification is a special form of the metaphor in which life is attributed to inanimate objects or the characteristics of persons are attributed to objects, animals, or even to abstract ideas.",
