     "title": "Apostrophe, Metonymy, and Synecdoche",
     "concept": "addressing the absent, and two figures of substitution",
     "summary": "Apostrophe directly addresses the absent or the lifeless as if present. Metonymy substitutes one object for another closely associated with it; synecdoche substitutes a part for the whole or the whole for a part.",
     "explanation": "**Apostrophe** is like personification but adds one thing: a direct *address*. When we speak straight to an inanimate object or to an absent person as though present, we are using apostrophe. Tennyson's cry, \"O Sea!\", and the plea \"Backward, turn backward, O Time, in your flight\" are both apostrophes, because the writer turns and speaks to the thing itself. The next two figures both work by **substitution**. In **metonymy** we name one object in place of another to which it is so closely tied that naming the one calls up the other. \"The pupils are reading George Eliot\" puts the author for her books; \"Strike for your altars and your fires\" puts altars and fires for home and country. In **synecdoche** the substitution is between a part and a whole: we name a part for the whole or a whole for the part. \"A babe, two summers old\" puts *summers* (a part of the year) for whole years; \"Give us this day our daily bread\" puts *bread*, one food, for food in general. The difference is worth fixing in mind: metonymy substitutes by *association*, synecdoche by the relation of *part and whole*.",
     "lead": "These three readings treat apostrophe, the figure that directly addresses the absent or the lifeless, and the two substitution figures, metonymy and synecdoche. Watch for the older examples of addressing the Sea and Time, of reading 'George Eliot,' and of a babe 'two summers old.'",
     "original": "91. Apostrophe. - Apostrophe is like personification, but has an additional characteristic. When we directly address inanimate objects or the absent as if they were present, we call the figure of speech thus formed apostrophe.\n\nThe following are examples of apostrophe: -\n\nBreak, break, break, At the foot of thy crags, O Sea! - TENNYSON.\n\nBackward, turn backward, O Time, in your flight, Make me a child again just for to-night! Mother, come back from the echoless shore, Take me again to your heart as of yore. - ELIZABETH AKERS ALLEN.\n\n92. Metonymy. - Metonymy consists in substituting one object for another, the two being so closely associated that the mention of one suggests the other.\n\nThe pupils are reading George Eliot. Each hamlet heard the call. Strike for your altars and your fires. Gray hairs should be respected.\n\n93. Synecdoche. - Synecdoche consists in substituting a part of anything for the whole or a whole for the part.\n\nA babe, two summers old. Give us this day our daily bread. Ring out the thousand years of woe, Ring in the thousand years of peace. Fifty masts are on the ocean.",
